When Mike McCurry was asked

what the number-one role of a.

spokesman is, he immediately replied
that it is essential to remember who
your boss is. _ ‘

Not Bill Clinton, but the people of
the United States. - .

“It’s the only reason why you stand
and answer the questions to begin
with,” said McCurry, explaining that
his role as White House press secretary
was not to defend the president but
rather to inform the American public of
things they needed to know.

McCurry spoke to about 450 of his
former bosses in the William Pitt Union
Monday night. It was his first speaking
engagement after leaving his executive
office post two weeks ago, a position he
had held since January 1995.

Three and a half years, about 550
press conferences and countless “no
comments” later, McCurry made Pitt
the launching pad for his post—White
House career. McCurry chose Pitt as his
“test site” because it was the ﬁrst uni-
versity to ask him to speak, and he said
he heard of Pitt’s “great tradition” from
others in the White House.

Instead of reading the speech he
had prepared, McCurry asked members
of the audience to participate in an
impromptu press conference. Over half
the night was devoted to a question and
answer period open to all, as long lines

formed behind the two microphones.

The questions could have continued

well into the night but ended after an

' hour and 15 minutes.

With questions ranging from cur-
rent global economic crises to the state
of affairs in the Middle East to his
future plans after life in the White
House, questions about the Monica
Lewinsky scandal were inevitably
fielded.

McCur1y’s response was the same
as it has been since the onset of the
media frenzy over Lewinsky.

“I elected to keep myself ignorant
of the details of the [Lewinsky] rela-
tionship,” .McCurry said. He explained
he wanted his money to go toward his
children’s school tuition rather than
legal fees if he were to be subpoenaed
in the Kenneth Starr investigation.

“Sometimes not knowing the
answer is better than not being able to
answer it truthfully,” said McCurry.

McCurry spent a great deal of time
with the president, but purposely kept
himself distant from Clinton’s personal

life. However, he was not devoid of /

opinions regarding the effect the scan-
dal would have on Clinton’s term in
office and the future of American poli-
tics. ' ‘ ‘ '

