Recent Oakland visitor wins Nobel Peace Prize  

Jason Gallinger
Asslstant News Editor

The winners of the Nobel Peace
Prize were announced last week,
and one of the men who received
the award recently spoke’ in

. ‘Pittsburgh.

The Nobel Committee gave the

Peace Prize to two men who have .

been instrumental in bringing peace
to Northern Ireland.

David Trimble, leader of the
Ulster Unionist Party, and John
Hume, head of the predominantly
Roman Catholic Social Democratic
Labour Party, will share the nearly
$1 million purse that accompanies
the award. The two had been bitter
enemies in the past but managed to

work together for peace. _

Trimble spoke at the Twentieth
Century Club in Oakland Oct. 9,
during a forum sponsored by the
Irish Institute of Pittsburgh. The
stop here was part of a 12—city tour
designed to drumup American
investment in Northern Ireland.

Trimble and Seamus Mallon, of
the Social Democratic Labour Party,
discussed the Good‘ Friday
Agreement signed on April 10,
which people around the world
hoped would end the Violence in
Northern Ireland.

The agreement created a 108-
member Northern Ireland Assembly
and a 12-member executive com-
mittee comprised of representatives
of the major political parties. The

Assembly will oversee the handling
of local issues. . .

Both menvemphasized the need
for investment in Northern Ireland
to help maintain the stability of the
peace accord. Successful mainte-
nance of the agreement could serve
as an example to other countries
gripped by political turmoil, they
said. ‘

Trimble‘ and Mallon said they

are confident the peace accord will ,

last as long as the Irish Republican
Army does not return to its violent
ways of the past.

Trimble said one of the major
questions that has plagued the peace
process is whether the IRA-has gen-
uinely turned away from violence in
favor of embracing peace.

