second author to read in the
Pittsburgh Contemporary Writers
Series, sponsored by Pitt’s English
Writing program. ' ,

Kingston, an American of
Chinese decent, said the title of the
book refers to three legendary tales
she said were burned in one of
China’s historic library fires.‘ “The

Fifth Book of Peace” details
Kingston’s attempts to rush home to
save her manuscript while listening
to a radio report of the fire on her
car radio.

Kingston also had a second
vision that she amused the audience
with. She jokingly claimed that her
father caused the fire, claiming he
wanted her book. When Kingston’s
first book, “Woman Warrior,”
became a success in 1976, she said
her father was jealous.

Many people in the audience
laughed when Kingston said her
mother used to “scold” her father
for not being able to produce any
poems of his own. ’ A

“You used to be a poet. Where
are the poems, poet?” said
Kingston, quoting her mother.

Kingston said her “dramatic
reaction” after the fire left her
unable to read or write. She added
that she believes a major reason the
majority of modern literature is so
depressing is because writing is
such a solitary, personalact.

