Removal of transitional program
cr step in right direction

Due to the increasing num-
ber of applicants and the limited
amount of. space available for
incoming students, the
University of Pittsburgh has

decided‘ to eliminate its Summer

Transitional Education Program.

STEP is a program designed to
"help applicants with low SAT

scores or low grades, who have
the potential to do well, prepare
for college.

As a University seeking to
make headway on the academic
circuit, improve the quality of its
students and raise its admissions

standards, removing a‘transition- '

al program for marginal students
is a good idea. If Yale, Harvard
or even some of the major public
universities don’t have programs’
like this one, why should Pitt?
Though the STEP program
does give marginally accepted
students a chance to do well in
college by giving them a solid
start, it is a program that could
potentially turn away a more
qualiﬁed student in favor of the
marginal student, considering
Pitt’s limited space. Programs
for disabled and foreign students
should still be offered, but pro-
grams for students whose only
problem is a slight incompeten-
cy in, math or English composi-

tion are simply not necessary.

. Everyone deserves a chance
to succeed, but STEP is not the
way to’do'it. If a student with

marginal grades wants to attend’

college but can barely meet
Pitt’s admissions criteria, the
student should enroll at one of
Pitt’s branch campuses, a col-
lege with lower admissions stan-
dards or a community college. If

they have potential, they will

prove themselves by getting
good grades .and as a result will

‘ be able to transfer to Pitt’s main '

campus.

STEP, a requirement for
marginal students before they
enter their freshman year, teach-
es math and English composi-
tion skills — skills students
should have picked up in high
school. Disabled students and
foreign students with high
grades but limited English skills

’ should still be helped, but help

should not be given to high
school graduates who have trou-

ble remembering their basic.

algebra.

If these students are not
ready to come to college, they
are -not ready to come to college.

There should be no need for

STEP for a college with high
academic aspirations.

