Last year I was confronted by a scrap-
py young punk who thought he could

write. His name was Kevin Carey, and for ,
some reason our minds locked onto a new ~

notion of what it means to be alive in
Pittsburgh. We were both too juvenile to
really understand the implications of our
thoughts. We’d spend late nights shucking
responsibility and devoting whims to
excess and drunken merriness. We have
matured since then, however. We have
realized the importance of the journey, and
we have made a pledge to embark across
life on the raft of perception. So I invite
all who have taken something from my

,poem (and last_week’s urban poem by

Kevin Carey), to send us any good drugs
that may be laying around. If there’s one
thing I’ve learned, it’s that the proper
amount of narcotics will liven up any
mundane affair. Even if it is a night at the
opera.

Two reminders in closing: The path
you’re traveling on should always be your
own,- and cheese is best when served from
a can.

Eric Anderson and Kevin Carey may be the
same brain divided into two bodies —— one
an Irish Catholic drunk and the other just
a drunk. -

